(16, 4, 'Factory Management Programme', '2010-03-09', '2010-03-12', '2010-02-16', 'LUMS, Lahore', '<p>Pakistan&rsquo;s manufacturing industry is generally focused at producing goods that are low to medium technology manufactures. Although the level of technology sophistication varies across most industries, the magnitude of human intervention in running production floors and producing goods is considered significant across all. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nFurthermore, globalization and international competition demands from local industries to &lsquo;reduce time to market&rsquo;, &lsquo;cut down its costs&rsquo; and &lsquo;provide better value&rsquo; to customers on a continual basis. Hence the use of better management practices on production floors becomes inevitable in such a situation in order to enhance performance and increase productivity.</p>', '<p>This programme is designed to expose some of the contemporary management concepts, tools and techniques that are considered essential for achieving operational excellence on the manufacturing floors of medium to large organizations. <br />\r\n&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />\r\nThis Factory Management Programme would allow the participants to re-engineer the existing &amp; introduce new best management practices in their respective areas. In order to provide optimum value, this programme has been designed with the issues and challenges in the context of Pakistani manufacturing organizations. The programme faculty are equipped with international experience as well as the local industrial knowledge to deliver a learning experience which is likely to be practical, actionable &amp; self enduring.</p>', '<p>In this programme the following thematic areas would be included:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp;&nbsp; Operations Strategy</strong><br />\r\nProduction operations have to make strategic choices from among the factors -&nbsp; lead time, cost, quality and flexibility and formulate a strategy that is best suited to deliver the type of products that are being produced. Having a clear strategy for production operations helps utilizing available resources efficiently and effectively. Such a strategy can have medium to long term implications on the performance of the plant.<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp; Management Style </strong><br />\r\nFor a long period of time the management style of Pakistani firms especially the middle management level is considered lacking best management approaches. Change capability, delegation of power, teamwork, and employee development are some of the elements that need to be embraced by the personnel at middle management levels.<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong>&nbsp; Responsiveness </strong><br />\r\nThis is one of the most important factors which emerges as a consequence of changing market requirements in global market places.&nbsp; Market requirements can change in terms of <em>volume, product specifications, product type, time to market to name a few</em>. Responsiveness is the ability of an organization to respond to these changes successfully. Responsiveness calls for different managerial and organizational approaches for <em>reducing throughput time, breaking bottlenecks, improving resource utilization, standardizing production specifications</em> to name a few.<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong> Production Costing</strong><br />\r\nMany Pakistani firms do not put due emphasis on the cost of production. It is becoming extremely important for manufacturing organizations to value each action that is carried out on production floors so that high-cost non-value-added activities could be removed from the system.</p>', '<p>The programme is designed for the middle level managers of manufacturing organizations. This programme would also be appropriate for those who are responsible for meeting market demand as well as improving production operations.</p>', '<p>The senior faculty of LUMS incorporates the latest research and business concepts into the classroom teaching through <strong>case studies, lectures, video/computer simulations, and small group activities. </strong>We offer an interactive, actioanable learning experience for you to develop personal and professional strengths and lead your organisation into an increasingly competitive environment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The case method of teaching is a special strength of LUMS.</strong><br />\r\nThe university is at the forefront in developing and using cases in its various programmes. Cases describe actual business situations and bring into the classroom, problems and opportunities faced by practicing managers. The participants analyse problems, evaluate alternatives and recommend appropriate solutions which help enhance decision-making abilities, and problem-solving skills.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo enrich the learning process REDC faculty shares its experience and knowledge culled from the latest academic literature and research, as well as insights gained from working with companies as researchers, consultants, and board members. The extensive experience of the faculty in planning and conducting executive programmes ensures an interactive and stimulating classroom experience for you.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Peer group learning is an integral part of the learning process.</strong><br />\r\nThe dynamic exchange of knowledge and experience among successful individuals from different organisations and functions enhances learning. Valuable ideas and insights are shared with fellow participants and faculty in and out of the classroom. Group study provides a forum where you benefit from the diversity of views, perspectives and abilities of other team members. Our programme also provides excellent <strong>networking opportunities</strong>.</p>', 55, '<p>PhD, Loughborough University, U.K.<br />\r\nMSc, Loughborough University, U.K.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Research Interests: </strong>Behavior Modeling of Complex Organizations, Supply Chain Design,  Business Process Improvement</p>\r\n<p>Before joining LUMS in December 2005, Dr. Chatha was a Research Associate (Manufacturing Management) at Loughborough University, U.K. Over the years, Dr. Chatha has built his affiliation with Society of Manufacturing Engineers, Institute of Industrial Engineers and Pakistan Engineering Council. He has more than 5 years of versatile research experience in Systems Dynamics, Agile Manufacturing Philosophies, Complex Organization Design and Business Process Improvement.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Other Faculty<br />\r\n</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Jamshed H. Khan</strong></p>\r\n<p>PhD, University of Texas at Arlington</p>\r\n<p><strong>Arif I. Rana</strong></p>\r\n<p>PhD, Rennselaer Polytechnic Institute</p>', '', '<p><strong>Programme Fee:&nbsp; Rs 54,000</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe fee includes tuition cost, reading material, tea and lunch served during the programme. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you wish to avail accommodation at LUMS, there will be additional fee of <strong>Rs 30,000</strong>. It includes accommodation, breakfasts and dinners for the duration of the programme. However, any extra charges such as telephones, extra meals etc should be paid on departure. You may check-in on the evening preceding the start date of the programme and check out the morning after the programme ends. You are, however, requested to inform us of the time of your arrival and departure.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Accommodation</strong></p>\r\n<p><br />\r\nWe offer single bed accommodation at the Rausing Executive Centre. Each bedroom with attached bathroom is equipped with mini-fridge, writing desk and direct dial STD/ISD telephone and cable TV. All bedrooms at REC are internet-ready. <em>Please note we do not provide accommodation for drivers accompanying participants.</em></p>\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Payment</strong></p>\r\n<p><br />\r\nPayment is due upon receipt of the acceptance letter along with the invoice. Ple