(28, 12, 'Building Sustainable Brand Equity', '2010-06-01', '2010-06-04', '2010-05-11', 'LUMS, Lahore', '<p>Building powerful brands continues to be the most challenging frontier of marketing. Fundamentally, a brand&rsquo;s continuity depends on its ability to sustain itself. Regardless of your view of the world, your brand remains your company&rsquo;s most valuable asset that can help you sustain your business in turbulent times. Understanding how your brand creates value for you, is the key to maintaining market leadership or establishing it in the first place. We also continue to see a trend of increasingly sophisticated outlook on managing brands, and growing importance on understanding the drivers of brand value.&nbsp; Nowadays brands may represent invaluable intangible assets, creating and nurturing a strong brand poses considerable challenges. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nCharting the course for successful brand management requires a multifaceted perspective, even if it is delivered through one brand. A connected and holistic approach to brand management is prerequisite. While it is essential that companies establish distinctive brands in their marketing plans, they must also emphasize differentiation and trust when marketing the branded product. This is especially critical for companies selling intangible products because trust itself can be the most significant differentiator. Digital and media technologies have opened many new channels of communication and information, giving companies the opportunity to develop much closer relationships between their brands and their consumers. As a result, both companies and their brands have to establish the type of strong personality and confident attitude that can engage consumers, inspire trust, obtain advocacy, and sustain active interest and involvement. Hard evidence is critically important to any brand case, and an evidentiary overlay can be a tremendous asset in building and communicating a uniquely compelling brand position.</p>', '<p>The concept of customer based brand equity can provide marketers with valuable perspective and a common denominator to interpret the potential effects and tradeoffs of various strategies and tactics for their brands. This four day programme on building sustainable brand equity aims to provide a comprehensive and state-of-the-art thinking about the subjects of brands, brand equity, and strategic brand management &ndash; the design and implementation of brand management programmes and activities to build, measure, and manage customer based brand equity. A key feature of the programme is the opportunity to use real market data for tracking of brand&rsquo;s positioning and performance.</p>', '<p>Following topic areas will be covered in the programme;<br />\r\n<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Foundations of successful brands<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Determinants of strong customer-based brand equity<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The steps of strong brand building<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Creating depth and breadth of brand awareness<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Choosing brand elements to build brand personality<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Leveraging secondary brand associations to build brand equity<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Making a good &lsquo;brand mantra&rsquo; <br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Integrated marketing communications to build brand equity<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tracking critical aspects of brand equity using market information<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Converting brand response to create an intense, active loyalty relationship between customers and brand<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Launching new successful brands<br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe programme delivery platform consists of case studies of leading brands, lectures, group discussions and speaker sessions plus brand tracking using real market research data. <br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', '<p>This programme is meant for senior business executives, marketing specialists, brand managers, executives from advertising and promotions industry, managers from media and communication sector, managers from public sector and non government organizations who desire to deepen their understanding of latest brand equity management concepts and practice.</p>', '<p>The senior faculty of LUMS incorporates the latest research and business concepts into the classroom teaching through <strong>case studies, lectures, video/computer simulations, and small group activities.</strong> We offer an interactive, actionable learning experience for you to develop personal and professional strengths and lead your organization into an increasingly competitive environment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The case method of teaching is a special strength of LUMS.</strong><br />\r\nThe university is at the forefront in developing and using cases in its various programmes. Cases describe actual business situations and bring into the classroom, problems and opportunities faced by practicing managers. The participants analyze problems, evaluate alternatives and recommend appropriate solutions which help enhance decision-making abilities, and problem-solving skills.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nTo enrich the learning process REDC faculty shares its experience and knowledge culled from the latest academic literature and research, as well as insights gained from working with companies as researchers, consultants, and board members. The extensive experience of the faculty in planning and conducting executive programmes ensures an interactive and stimulating classroom experience for you.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Peer group learning is an integral part of the learning process.</strong><br />\r\nThe dynamic exchange of knowledge and experience among successful individuals from different organizations and functions enhances learning. Valuable ideas and insights are shared with fellow participants and faculty in and out of the classroom. Group study provides a forum where you benefit from the diversity of views, perspectives and abilities of other team members. Our programme also provides excellent <strong>networking opportunities.</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 38, '<p>Associate Professor of Competitiveness, Strategy &amp; Marketing<br />\r\nPhD, University of Cambridge<br />\r\n<br />\r\nDr. Faheem ul Islam teaches Corporate Strategy, Business Policy, Marketing Management, Consumer Behavior, Microeconomics of Competitiveness, International Business, International Marketing, Retail Operations Management, Marketing of Technology and Enterprise Management to the M.B.A. and Executive M.B.A. students. He has taught several topics in Rausing Executive Centre at LUMS including Marketing Management, Pricing Strategy, Corporate Strategy, Managing Transition of Public Sector Organizations, Service Marketing, Social Sector Marketing and Organizational Development. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nHis research interests include Business Strategy, Industry Competitiveness, and Regional Economic<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', '', '<p><strong>Programme Fee:&nbsp; Rs 54,000</strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe fee includes tuition cost, reading material, tea and lunch served during the programme. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIf you wish to avail accommodation at LUMS, there will be additional fee of <strong>Rs 30,000</strong>. It includes accommodation, breakfasts and dinners for the duration of the programme. However, any extra charges such as telephones, extra meals etc should be paid on departure. You may check-in on the evening preceding the start date of the programme and check out the morning after the programme ends. You are, however, requested to inform us of the time of your arrival and departure.</p>\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Accommodation</strong></p>\r\n<p><br />\r\nWe offer single bed accommodation at the Rausing Executive Centre. Each bedroom with attached bathroom is equipped with mini-fridge, writing desk and direct dial STD/ISD telephone and cable TV. All bedrooms at REC are internet-ready. <em>Please note we do not provide accommodation for drivers accompanying participants.</em></p>\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Payment</strong></p>\r\n<p><br />\r\nPayment is due upon receipt of the acceptance letter along with the invoice. Please ensure that the payment reaches the office BEFORE the start of the programme. Space in the programme may only be ensured after we receive the fee.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nOur preferred mode of payment is by cheque/banker&rsquo;s draft payable to Lahore University of Management Sciences. Please send the cheque to: <br />\r\n<br />\r\nMarketing Officer &ndash; Executive Education and Development<br />\r\nLahore University of Management Sciences<br />\r\nOpposite Sector &quot;U&quot;, DHA<br />\r\nLahore - 54792<br />\r\nTel: 92-42-35608000<br />\r\nExt.: 8243-8119<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<em> * The income of the University is exempt from tax under Clause 92 of Second Schedule of the Income Tax Ordinance 2001. Therefore, no tax is deductible from the fee at source. In case the tax is deducted please send us the tax challan with the cheque.<br />\r\n</em><br />\r\n<strong>Discount Policy</strong></p>\r\n<p><br />\r\nFor any executive programme, if more than two executives from the same organization participate, each additional participant after the first two gets a 30% discount on the programme fee. <br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>Substitutes/Transfers and Refunds </strong></p>\r\n<p><br />\r\nIf you are unable to attend a registered course we will accept a substitute until two working days before the programme. Substitute candidates will be subject to the same selection process as the original candidate. If you wish to cancel your name from a programme, please notify in writing at least five working days before the programme. Course fee will be refunded after deducting an application-processing fee of Rs. 10,000/-. There will be no refund for cancellation received after the withdrawal date or in case of no-show.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIt is possible to transfer to another programme within 2 years. The deposited fee will be carried forward after deducting the application-processing fee of Rs. 10,000/-. Please note that only one transfer is permitted. After 2 years the deposited fee will be forfeited. Transfers should be notified at least five working days before the programme.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nAll notifications of cancellations, substitutes and transfers must be confirmed in writing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nNote: REDC may cancel or postpone a programme due to insufficient enrolment or unforeseen circumstances. In this case, University will refund registration fee and is not responsible for any other related charges/expenses including cancellation/change charges by airlines and travel agencies. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn case of postponement, the fee may be transferred to the rescheduled offering of that programme or any other programme as an alternate to refund. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nThe University reserves the right to make changes in its programme policies and fees at any time. <br />\r\n<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'Senior Managers', NULL, 'Yes', 'N', 'Y', 4, 'a'),
(29, 12, 'Marketing Strategy', '2009-11-17', '2009-11-21', '2009-11-02', 'LUMS, Lahore', '<p>Identifying and seizing profitable business opportunities in a fast changing and competitive environment of the consumer and industrial market is the key to a successful business. As the customer needs, tastes and preferences change many of our current products become obsolete. Similarly, as the competition brings newer, cheaper and better products to the marketplace our loyal customers may move on. Successful companies must use disciplined marketing strategy to remain ahead of the competition in delivering value to their customers.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nMarketing strategy starts with understanding customer needs, wants, and perceptions to identify opportunities best matched with organizational resources and capabilities. It also entails continuous monitoring of competitive activities and pre-empting or thwarting them with better value propositions to customers. Finally, it requires managing a portfolio of old and new products in a way that a steady and growing profit stream for the organization is guaranteed<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', '<p>&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Selecting the customer to serve<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Which customer needs to fulfill<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Formulating the value proposition for the selected target market<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Synergies in the 4Ps of marketing<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Monitor competitors and trade to one&rsquo;s advantage<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Learn from the market experiences in order to dominate the market<br />\r\n&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; How does one become a solid marketing strategist?&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />\r\n<br />\r\nThis programme is designed to address all of the above and more. Based on a state-of-the-art marketing strategy simulation game, MARKSTRAT 3 coupled with cases and class lectures and discussions, this program will provide managers a rich and vivid experience of actually managing a portfolio of products in a ruthless marketing environment. Participant teams are formed by the programme management to optimally blend functional disciplines and work experience. Your team will need to make the right decisions on relevant target markets, precise product positioning, effective usage of development resources, and forecasting accurate demand and competitive activity, lest the competition beat you. All this in a realistic environment of constrained resources and budgets. You will get regular feedback on how you have performed in the form of market share change, and financial performance. Your team will have plenty of opportunities to learn from your mistakes and reposition or re-launch products with revised marketing expenditures. This however, will require your team to outperform very smart competitors. Watch out!&nbsp; Marketing Strategy will separate the men from the boys of marketing.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', '', '<p>This programme is aimed at CEOs, General Managers, Marketing, Product and Brand Managers from consumer and industrial goods and service companies. Top managers from other functional areas will also benefit by understanding the key role of Marketing Strategy in company profitability and survival.</p>', '<p>The senior faculty of LUMS incorporates the latest research and business concepts into the classroom teaching through <strong>case studies, lectures, video/computer simulations, and small group activities.</strong> We offer an interactive, actioanable learning experience for you to develop personal and professional strengths and lead your organisation into an increasingly competitive environment.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong>The case method of teaching is a special strength of LUMS.</strong><br />\r\nThe university is at the forefront in developing and using cases in its various programmes. Cases describe actual business situations and bring into the classroom, problems and opportunities faced